  "articleSummary": "The article critiques the flawed use of fixed-priority dropdowns (e.g., P1-P4) in project management tools like Jira, arguing that their rigidity leads to \"priority inflation\" (e.g., P0, P00) as teams encounter shifting priorities. It highlights how static labels fail to capture dynamic factors like urgency, business value, and stakeholder alignment, while analogies to CSS `z-index` wars and \"Bizzaro Trophy Rooms\" underscore the chaos of unbounded prioritization. The author advocates for flexible alternatives—numerical scales, composite scores, or frameworks like MoSCoW—to better reflect evolving priorities and reduce backlog clutter. Targeted at software teams and managers, the tone blends analytical critique with dry humor, urging a shift from \"engineering theater\" to pragmatic, forward-focused prioritization.",
